ttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout Europe, narratives about the past circulate at a dizzying speed, and producing and selling these narratives is big business. In museums, in cinema and opera houses, in schools, and even on the Internet, Europeans are using the power of performance to craft stories that ultimately define the ways their audiences understand and remember history. Performing the Past offers unparalleled insights into the philosophical, literary, musical, and historical frameworks within which the past has entered into the European imagination. The essays in this volume, from such internationally renowned scholars as Reinhart Koselleck, Jan Assmann, Jane Caplan, Marianne Hirsch, Leo Spitzer, Peter Burke, and Alessandro Portelli, investigate various national and disciplinary traditions to explain how Europeans see themselves in the past, in the present, and in the years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCollective memoryzEurope. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aAssmann, Aleida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssmann, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBottici, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaplan, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrijzenhout, Frans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoselleck, Reinhart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeerssen, Joep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLore